00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:25.910
HARVEY: We have today some
distinguished visitors,

00:00:25.910 --> 00:00:29.344
Tim Ray on piano and Eugene
Friesen on his cello.

00:00:29.344 --> 00:00:30.760
And they along
with another person

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:34.528
named Greg Hopkins form a
trio called Tre Corda, named

00:00:34.528 --> 00:00:36.384
for one of the
pedals on the piano.

00:00:36.384 --> 00:00:38.240
Tim Ray will explain it.

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:41.230
And as you know, they are
giving a concert this evening.

00:00:41.230 --> 00:00:45.126
So you will all be
coming to that concert,

00:00:45.126 --> 00:00:47.356
and I'll give you as I have
before the concert points

00:00:47.356 --> 00:00:50.932
to write your concert
reflections from.

00:00:50.932 --> 00:00:52.836
I'll send that out
later this afternoon.

00:00:52.836 --> 00:00:55.216
That's at Killian
tonight 8 o'clock.

00:00:55.216 --> 00:00:57.117
So you'll see the full group.

00:00:57.117 --> 00:00:58.450
But they're here this afternoon.

00:00:58.450 --> 00:01:01.796
So please give them
a warm welcome.

00:01:01.796 --> 00:01:02.700
FRIESEN: Thank you.

00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:03.160
HARVEY: Thanks.

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:03.560
RAY: Thank you.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:04.060
Thanks.

00:01:04.060 --> 00:01:09.294
So we're really glad to
be here, and as Mark said,

00:01:09.294 --> 00:01:10.710
we're playing the
concert tonight.

00:01:10.710 --> 00:01:12.418
So of course that's
the first requirement

00:01:12.418 --> 00:01:16.030
for passing the class is
that you have to come.

00:01:16.030 --> 00:01:17.877
We always make that joke.

00:01:17.877 --> 00:01:18.460
Nobody laughs.

00:01:18.460 --> 00:01:19.520
HARVEY: It's not a joke.

00:01:19.520 --> 00:01:20.420
RAY: It's not a joke.

00:01:20.420 --> 00:01:22.140
Oh that's why they don't laugh.

00:01:22.140 --> 00:01:22.740
OK.

00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:23.610
Now I get it.

00:01:23.610 --> 00:01:24.860
HARVEY: I'm very serious here.

00:01:24.860 --> 00:01:26.990
RAY: OK yeah.

00:01:26.990 --> 00:01:29.695
In just a little bit, we
want to get into playing

00:01:29.695 --> 00:01:34.420
and of course get you guys
playing as well, hopefully.

00:01:34.420 --> 00:01:38.010
Just a little bit about
what we do as a trio.

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:41.240
As Mark said, our trumpet
player Greg Hopkins

00:01:41.240 --> 00:01:42.170
will join us tonight.

00:01:42.170 --> 00:01:47.690
And then you'll see Greg next
week in the class as well.

00:01:47.690 --> 00:01:49.140
We are a trio.

00:01:49.140 --> 00:01:51.630
We've been together--
gosh, I guess

00:01:51.630 --> 00:01:55.290
it's getting to be about 12
years now, the three of us.

00:01:55.290 --> 00:01:58.520
And we do, it's an
unusual instrumentation.

00:01:58.520 --> 00:02:03.930
I mean at least unusual in
terms of traditional jazz trios

00:02:03.930 --> 00:02:05.380
because there's no base.

00:02:05.380 --> 00:02:06.650
There's no drums.

00:02:06.650 --> 00:02:09.520
It's also unusual in
a classical setting.

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:12.630
Usually a piano trio with
cello usually has a violin

00:02:12.630 --> 00:02:13.330
not trumpet.

00:02:13.330 --> 00:02:19.427
So we're a little bit of a
hybrid kind of formation.

00:02:19.427 --> 00:02:21.510
And it's something I had
the idea to put together,

00:02:21.510 --> 00:02:23.060
like I said, about 12 years ago.

00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:27.070
And a lot of what we
do is we play music

00:02:27.070 --> 00:02:29.490
that we compose,
Eugene and myself

00:02:29.490 --> 00:02:32.030
and Greg all write
for this group.

00:02:32.030 --> 00:02:33.260
We're all improvisers.

00:02:33.260 --> 00:02:37.150
So of course improvisation plays
a large part in what we do.

00:02:37.150 --> 00:02:38.850
But we also delve
into classical music.

00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:42.970
We delve into jazz,
Brazilian stuff.

00:02:42.970 --> 00:02:45.290
And that's all our
backgrounds as well.

00:02:45.290 --> 00:02:48.500
I mean, myself, Eugene, Greg--
we're all classically trained.

00:02:48.500 --> 00:02:50.690
Then we're also
jazz players and do

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:54.450
a lot of things outside
of this group as well.

00:02:54.450 --> 00:02:58.340
So besides that,
Eugene and I actually

00:02:58.340 --> 00:02:59.782
have to a duo that we do.

00:02:59.782 --> 00:03:02.240
We're going to actually play
a couple of songs from our duo

00:03:02.240 --> 00:03:04.920
repertoire because it's a
little hard to do the trio

00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:07.170
stuff without the third person.

00:03:07.170 --> 00:03:09.850
Although we might mess around
a little bit later with that,

00:03:09.850 --> 00:03:11.690
get you guys involved.

00:03:11.690 --> 00:03:15.307
But anything you want to say?

00:03:15.307 --> 00:03:15.890
FRIESEN: Sure.

00:03:15.890 --> 00:03:18.030
I mean Mark just told us
the first thing about what

00:03:18.030 --> 00:03:20.310
you guys have been
studying so far.

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:22.460
And how many of you
would categorize yourself

00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:25.520
as classically
trained musicians?

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:26.270
OK.

00:03:26.270 --> 00:03:28.500
Well that was my
background as well.

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:31.880
I was interested in
pop music and rock

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:33.990
really when I was in college.

00:03:33.990 --> 00:03:37.290
But I spent most of
my energy in really

00:03:37.290 --> 00:03:38.890
practicing classical repertoire.

00:03:38.890 --> 00:03:40.830
And it wasn't until I
got out a music school

00:03:40.830 --> 00:03:43.840
that I started to get a little
bit more serious about doing

00:03:43.840 --> 00:03:47.680
the kind of ear training that
you need for improvising.

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:50.320
And for me it's been
a lifelong process.

00:03:50.320 --> 00:03:53.590
I feel like I'm still
learning a lot about that

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:58.600
and learning to recognize chords
and to learn how to contribute

00:03:58.600 --> 00:04:02.185
to a harmonic environment
just by listening

00:04:02.185 --> 00:04:04.750
and by pitching in.

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:08.290
And but I've also had a
chance to do a lot of work

00:04:08.290 --> 00:04:10.080
with classically
trained musicians who

00:04:10.080 --> 00:04:11.380
have never tried before.

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:18.440
Kids of all ages, beginners,
middle school, high school

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:21.550
kids, and even
professionals who are really

00:04:21.550 --> 00:04:23.880
very afraid to improvise.

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:25.410
In fact, last year
I had a chance

00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:29.010
to do a presentation at the
American String Teachers

00:04:29.010 --> 00:04:31.490
Association on improvising.

00:04:31.490 --> 00:04:35.570
And I started this
presentation by asking,

00:04:35.570 --> 00:04:38.470
what are some of the things
that keep us classically trained

00:04:38.470 --> 00:04:40.520
musicians from improvising?

00:04:40.520 --> 00:04:42.700
And there were about 100
people are so in that room,

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:45.370
and everybody had
something to say.

00:04:45.370 --> 00:04:48.320
I mean I didn't realize
this could easily

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:50.430
have been the topic of
that whole presentation.

00:04:50.430 --> 00:04:54.910
People really inherit,
I think, in our training

00:04:54.910 --> 00:04:57.450
a tremendous amount
of inhibitions.

00:04:57.450 --> 00:04:59.950
Some of it is the
impossibly high standards

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:03.190
that we are kind of
imbued with as students.

00:05:03.190 --> 00:05:05.420
Some of which, of
course, is really

00:05:05.420 --> 00:05:08.010
good for motivating
our hard work.

00:05:08.010 --> 00:05:10.670
But a lot of which
really makes us kind of

00:05:10.670 --> 00:05:15.510
cower when we're in a situation
where we're encouraged

00:05:15.510 --> 00:05:17.520
to be creative
and play something

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:20.040
that we haven't
really rehearsed.

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:27.770
And so that's been kind of
the impetus of my teaching.

00:05:27.770 --> 00:05:29.730
And one thing
that's really helped

00:05:29.730 --> 00:05:34.270
me is setting some guidelines
that were comfortable for me

00:05:34.270 --> 00:05:36.370
as a classically trained player.

00:05:36.370 --> 00:05:39.780
So one of the first ways
that I felt I could improvise

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:44.740
was no wrong notes, completely
open, free improv stuff.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:46.610
And I understand you
guys get to do that

00:05:46.610 --> 00:05:49.360
each week with Tom Hall, right?

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:52.159
Am I correct in assuming
that at some point

00:05:52.159 --> 00:05:54.200
you do some improvising
where you're not worrying

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:56.460
about chords or scales
or things like that?

00:05:56.460 --> 00:05:58.610
It's really most about
interaction, right?

00:05:58.610 --> 00:06:01.050
And how it comes together
rhythmically maybe.

00:06:01.050 --> 00:06:03.210
I mean do you work on the
rhythmic side of things

00:06:03.210 --> 00:06:05.520
more that way, or is
it more intuitive kind

00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:07.240
of communicating?

00:06:07.240 --> 00:06:09.149
Could someone
answer that for me?

00:06:09.149 --> 00:06:11.690
AUDIENCE: Different things, and
different exercises, I guess.

00:06:11.690 --> 00:06:14.060
FRIESEN: So it's
different all the time,

00:06:14.060 --> 00:06:17.140
different guidelines for your
improv that you're doing there.

00:06:17.140 --> 00:06:18.560
Gotcha.

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:21.460
Well that was-- the free
improv part of things

00:06:21.460 --> 00:06:24.740
and not worrying about notes is
a tremendous liberator for me

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:26.730
as a classically trained player.

00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:30.820
And then the next thing
was playing diatonically.

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:36.840
Learning how to create something
that really had heart, that

00:06:36.840 --> 00:06:40.390
had shape, that had
personal expression for me,

00:06:40.390 --> 00:06:43.860
but that was kind
of limited in terms

00:06:43.860 --> 00:06:46.960
of how it wandered
from key to key.

00:06:46.960 --> 00:06:50.860
And maybe we could play "First
Ride" as an example of that.

00:06:50.860 --> 00:06:51.360
RAY: Sure.

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:52.250
That's great.

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:54.541
FRIESEN: I don't know where
Tim wanted to go with this.

00:06:54.541 --> 00:06:56.550
We're just kind of winging this.

00:06:56.550 --> 00:07:00.500
But for me this piece
that we're about to play

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:04.590
was really one of
the first improvs

00:07:04.590 --> 00:07:07.445
that I did that was a real
successful cello and piano

00:07:07.445 --> 00:07:07.945
improv.

00:07:07.945 --> 00:07:11.050
It happened to be recorded
in a great cathedral

00:07:11.050 --> 00:07:13.160
in New York, Saint
John the Divine.

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:18.439
And it had such a kind
of formal quality.

00:07:18.439 --> 00:07:20.480
It's something that I
wanted to play in concerts.

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:22.440
So we transcribed it.

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:24.800
We went by went back and
listened to the recording

00:07:24.800 --> 00:07:26.780
and really transcribed it.

00:07:26.780 --> 00:07:30.980
It's like when you have
an improv like this,

00:07:30.980 --> 00:07:33.750
it's kind of like capturing
lightning in a bottle in a way.

00:07:33.750 --> 00:07:36.050
And if you want to
duplicate it, you

00:07:36.050 --> 00:07:38.630
can take some of the themes
and stuff as the starting

00:07:38.630 --> 00:07:40.730
off points, but in
this case, it seemed

00:07:40.730 --> 00:07:44.080
to work so well as kind of
a thought through thing,

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:47.060
that we play it
as close as we can

00:07:47.060 --> 00:07:48.990
to the recording as possible.

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:51.970
Now the piano part is
pretty much Tim's invention.

00:07:51.970 --> 00:07:53.780
What he had from
the transcription

00:07:53.780 --> 00:07:57.060
were a few right hand
lines that Paul Halley,

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:00.080
the original
improviser, improvised.

00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:03.430
But the cello part is
really-- it's written.

00:08:03.430 --> 00:08:05.680
It's the same cello part
that I originally improvised.

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:19.544
So this is called "First Ride."

00:08:19.544 --> 00:08:20.044
RAY: Ready?

00:08:20.044 --> 00:08:22.040
FRIESEN: Yeah.

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:24.535
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:12:55.736 --> 00:12:56.780
[AUDIENCE APPLAUSE]

00:12:56.780 --> 00:12:57.280
RAY: Thanks.

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:03.790
and the construction had
the third in that chord.

00:13:03.790 --> 00:13:05.830
I don't know if you
caught that, whatever

00:13:05.830 --> 00:13:09.590
that machine is out there.

00:13:09.590 --> 00:13:14.380
RAY: So I'd love to get
some of your thoughts

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:15.950
and some of your questions.

00:13:15.950 --> 00:13:21.880
But basically that whole
thing that you heard just now,

00:13:21.880 --> 00:13:26.130
as Eugene said, was all
originally freely improvised,

00:13:26.130 --> 00:13:29.420
but in a diatonic setting
meaning we really never

00:13:29.420 --> 00:13:31.490
left the key of D major, right?

00:13:31.490 --> 00:13:32.934
I mean basically.

00:13:32.934 --> 00:13:35.350
I mean, you see I've got all
these pages of transcription,

00:13:35.350 --> 00:13:38.770
but it's all-- we might
try little exercise where

00:13:38.770 --> 00:13:41.610
we do that with some of you
where diatonic-- we're staying

00:13:41.610 --> 00:13:44.730
in one key, but we're just
moving the chords around,

00:13:44.730 --> 00:13:47.320
moving the roots of these
chords around, doing

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:49.380
some improvisations,
and then doing

00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:53.940
figures, motives,
melodies based on that.

00:13:53.940 --> 00:13:56.810
Were there any questions,
any observations,

00:13:56.810 --> 00:13:59.720
commentary, criticism?

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:00.505
Yes,

00:14:00.505 --> 00:14:01.130
HARVEY: Adrian.

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:01.510
RAY: Adrian.

00:14:01.510 --> 00:14:02.010
Thank you.

00:14:02.010 --> 00:14:04.538
ADRIAN: I was wondering I
guess whether like there

00:14:04.538 --> 00:14:06.274
was some sort of
design framework

00:14:06.274 --> 00:14:09.498
that had been pre-planned,
like even some chord

00:14:09.498 --> 00:14:11.480
progressions that you guys do?

00:14:11.480 --> 00:14:12.282
FRIESEN: Nothing.

00:14:12.282 --> 00:14:13.490
ADRIAN: Everything was just--

00:14:13.490 --> 00:14:14.073
FRIESEN: Yeah.

00:14:16.620 --> 00:14:19.300
RAY: Thanks.

00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:20.976
Cool, yeah.

00:14:20.976 --> 00:14:22.698
AUDIENCE: So the
original theme actually

00:14:22.698 --> 00:14:24.340
reminded me a lot
of Cannon in D.

00:14:24.340 --> 00:14:25.550
RAY: Of Cannon in D?

00:14:25.550 --> 00:14:29.246
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
where you started.

00:14:29.246 --> 00:14:31.158
[INAUDIBLE]

00:14:31.158 --> 00:14:34.182
[PLAYING CELLO]

00:14:34.182 --> 00:14:35.140
FRIESEN: Is the melody.

00:14:38.550 --> 00:14:41.020
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I don't if
it's just because of the title

00:14:41.020 --> 00:14:43.182
or just because
it's [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:43.182 --> 00:14:45.140
RAY: That might of had
something to do with it.

00:14:45.140 --> 00:14:50.020
I mean, I'm sure you probably
know when you're improvising,

00:14:50.020 --> 00:14:52.509
you know you're
all you're always

00:14:52.509 --> 00:14:53.925
drawing from things
that you know.

00:14:53.925 --> 00:14:57.020
Drawing from music that you've
heard, drawing of course,

00:14:57.020 --> 00:15:00.230
from the people around you
who are improvising as well.

00:15:00.230 --> 00:15:02.850
So there's certainly
plenty of times

00:15:02.850 --> 00:15:05.190
when I'm improvising
and I'll play something

00:15:05.190 --> 00:15:08.580
and I'll be like, Oh, I
think that was the theme

00:15:08.580 --> 00:15:12.137
song to some TV show from
the '70s without really

00:15:12.137 --> 00:15:12.720
intentionally.

00:15:12.720 --> 00:15:15.260
I mean obviously jazz
players will intentionally

00:15:15.260 --> 00:15:17.540
throw in little quotes
for humorous effect.

00:15:17.540 --> 00:15:21.599
But oftentimes, they don't
come out intentionally.

00:15:21.599 --> 00:15:22.390
They just come out.

00:15:22.390 --> 00:15:26.230
And that's sometimes
the fun part of it.

00:15:26.230 --> 00:15:28.480
FRIESEN: I've heard it said
that you are what you eat.

00:15:28.480 --> 00:15:32.050
You know that expression?

00:15:32.050 --> 00:15:34.710
Certainly true for
us improvisers.

00:15:34.710 --> 00:15:39.020
What you know and what
you listen to really

00:15:39.020 --> 00:15:41.110
plays a huge part
in what you access

00:15:41.110 --> 00:15:44.095
when you're really
and truly improvising.

00:15:44.095 --> 00:15:46.220
Although there's another
thing that I might mention

00:15:46.220 --> 00:15:51.930
about this particular piece
is that at least for me, there

00:15:51.930 --> 00:15:55.180
was something about the
acoustics of the cathedral that

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:58.840
really activated my
imagination in a different way

00:15:58.840 --> 00:16:01.560
than it had ever been before.

00:16:01.560 --> 00:16:05.740
The way that the cello
just rose up in the room

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:11.710
somehow shifted my focus
from me and from my technique

00:16:11.710 --> 00:16:13.220
to the room.

00:16:13.220 --> 00:16:17.420
I mean it was almost like there
was this other kind of presence

00:16:17.420 --> 00:16:19.860
in there that I
was tapping into.

00:16:19.860 --> 00:16:23.890
And it was an important
experience for me.

00:16:23.890 --> 00:16:28.190
And oftentimes when I'm in
an improvisational situation,

00:16:28.190 --> 00:16:30.530
I place myself back
in the cathedral

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:32.140
because I really
felt like that was

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:36.500
where my voice as an
improviser was born.

00:16:36.500 --> 00:16:39.470
It was the first time I had
that experience of really being

00:16:39.470 --> 00:16:43.050
the music and not being a cello
player or even being a person.

00:16:47.190 --> 00:16:50.030
RAY: Any other
comments or questions?

00:16:50.030 --> 00:16:52.625
CHRIS: Not really a
question, but after hearing

00:16:52.625 --> 00:16:56.432
that you said that the
[INAUDIBLE] design [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:56.432 --> 00:16:58.707
That was really
inspiring that you

00:16:58.707 --> 00:17:00.705
managed to come up with
something so varied.

00:17:00.705 --> 00:17:02.830
Because I am really interested
in things like that.

