Because I really like the
idea of trying to improvise

00:17:05.530 --> 00:17:07.800
like that.

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:09.150
Just a simple idea.

00:17:09.150 --> 00:17:11.686
And I guess that's my
favorite way of improvising.

00:17:11.686 --> 00:17:13.938
But I always find
a sense of struggle

00:17:13.938 --> 00:17:17.373
to come up of with a whole
variety of interesting things

00:17:17.373 --> 00:17:19.819
maybe just from that
simple beginning.

00:17:19.819 --> 00:17:21.756
That's really, really
cool that that--

00:17:21.756 --> 00:17:23.880
FRIESEN: Can you hear what
he's saying well enough?

00:17:23.880 --> 00:17:25.500
Yeah.

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:27.550
I mean maybe one of the
things he's hinting at

00:17:27.550 --> 00:17:30.890
is the power there
is in limitation.

00:17:30.890 --> 00:17:32.990
That when you really
set boundaries

00:17:32.990 --> 00:17:35.580
about what your language
is going to be sometimes

00:17:35.580 --> 00:17:38.220
that can be really liberating.

00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:43.610
And in my case, with my limited
improv skills at that time--

00:17:43.610 --> 00:17:45.820
that was a 1986
when we did that.

00:17:45.820 --> 00:17:49.550
I was really a pretty
new improviser then.

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:53.670
The fact that we were
in an environment

00:17:53.670 --> 00:17:55.530
where I could use
my open strings,

00:17:55.530 --> 00:17:59.550
my harmonics, you know, I knew
what key we were in, really

00:17:59.550 --> 00:18:01.150
helped me so much.

00:18:01.150 --> 00:18:04.040
There's something about that
that just calmed me down,

00:18:04.040 --> 00:18:07.360
and I think that that calmness
and the incredible acoustics

00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:10.880
of the place helped for
this kind of magical moment

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:12.300
to happen.

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:15.860
Because it's a special moment.

00:18:15.860 --> 00:18:18.590
A piece like that
is something that

00:18:18.590 --> 00:18:20.760
really captured our
attention in a special way.

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:22.620
And that's why we
want to transcribe it.

00:18:22.620 --> 00:18:24.440
That doesn't happen
every time we sit down

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:26.560
to play something compelling.

00:18:26.560 --> 00:18:28.980
But it is amazing
what can happen

00:18:28.980 --> 00:18:34.050
with kind of a limited
palette of harmony,

00:18:34.050 --> 00:18:37.380
I guess you could say.

00:18:37.380 --> 00:18:41.640
How that can ignite this
kind of passion and feeling

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:43.910
of warmth and rapture.

00:18:43.910 --> 00:18:45.620
And what are some
other adjectives

00:18:45.620 --> 00:18:46.840
you would use for that music?

00:18:57.818 --> 00:18:58.830
RAY: Cool.

00:18:58.830 --> 00:19:00.190
FRIESEN: No they've got it.

00:19:00.190 --> 00:19:01.220
Some more adjectives.

00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:03.840
How would you describe it?

00:19:03.840 --> 00:19:05.650
Does it sound like
church music or?

00:19:08.821 --> 00:19:09.730
AUDIENCE: Just calm.

00:19:09.730 --> 00:19:11.630
FRIESEN: Calm.

00:19:11.630 --> 00:19:15.030
Maybe that's the
diatomic part of it.

00:19:15.030 --> 00:19:18.137
It's very grounded in that way.

00:19:18.137 --> 00:19:19.091
RAY: Yeah, definitely.

00:19:19.091 --> 00:19:24.650
Yeah, I mean I think the other
thing that-- I'm sorry, Chris.

00:19:24.650 --> 00:19:26.100
Thank you.

00:19:26.100 --> 00:19:29.840
Chris, at least in
my mind was when

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:33.610
he was talking about sort
of how much can come out

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:37.290
of a very small amount
of starter material,

00:19:37.290 --> 00:19:39.211
if you want to call it that.

00:19:39.211 --> 00:19:44.310
I think part of that
is also as Eugene said.

00:19:44.310 --> 00:19:46.322
It's sometimes having
the limitations of just,

00:19:46.322 --> 00:19:48.030
we're going to play
in D major, let's see

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:51.350
what happens, can
trigger these things.

00:19:51.350 --> 00:19:53.570
I think some of the other
thing too is sometimes

00:19:53.570 --> 00:19:57.920
when you're doing essentially
what I would consider freely

00:19:57.920 --> 00:20:02.200
improvising, you're
always trying

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:03.770
to-- you're always listening.

00:20:03.770 --> 00:20:10.340
You're always trying to think in
a larger form, a larger format.

00:20:10.340 --> 00:20:14.570
You know I mean all the music
that we love has sections.

00:20:14.570 --> 00:20:18.920
All the great
Mozart sonatas they

00:20:18.920 --> 00:20:23.190
have different sections
that are contrasting.

00:20:23.190 --> 00:20:24.510
Same with a great jazz piece.

00:20:24.510 --> 00:20:27.230
They have different sections--
contrasting sections,

00:20:27.230 --> 00:20:30.530
loud parts, soft
parts, a section that

00:20:30.530 --> 00:20:32.970
features a particular soloist,
a section the features

00:20:32.970 --> 00:20:34.330
the ensemble.

00:20:34.330 --> 00:20:37.490
You know, these are
all things we're

00:20:37.490 --> 00:20:42.550
trying to recreate in maybe not
necessarily a conscious way,

00:20:42.550 --> 00:20:46.640
although I mean, you could
be more conscious about it.

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:48.780
But even when you're
just freely improvising,

00:20:48.780 --> 00:20:51.320
and again, you might be working
on these kinds of things

00:20:51.320 --> 00:20:53.570
already.

00:20:53.570 --> 00:20:56.570
You're always kind of
listening for-- your listening

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:57.330
as you're playing.

00:20:57.330 --> 00:21:00.230
You're kind of thinking
like, OK maybe it's

00:21:00.230 --> 00:21:02.290
time to come down and
do a quiet section.

00:21:02.290 --> 00:21:04.260
Or maybe this is building
up to a big section.

00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:05.510
Maybe this is the climax.

00:21:05.510 --> 00:21:06.470
Was that the climax?

00:21:06.470 --> 00:21:07.020
I don't know.

00:21:07.020 --> 00:21:08.990
Let's see where it goes.

00:21:08.990 --> 00:21:11.120
But you're always
kind of-- I don't

00:21:11.120 --> 00:21:14.580
want to say that you're
always judging and evaluating,

00:21:14.580 --> 00:21:19.450
but in a certain
way the feelings

00:21:19.450 --> 00:21:23.800
that you develop when you play
a great piece of classical music

00:21:23.800 --> 00:21:26.860
or a great jazz
piece, these feelings

00:21:26.860 --> 00:21:30.110
you're trying to recreate in
a freely improvised setting.

00:21:30.110 --> 00:21:32.830
And often times you
can go back and you

00:21:32.830 --> 00:21:36.500
can look through
what you just did.

00:21:36.500 --> 00:21:38.230
With my students--
Eugene and I both

00:21:38.230 --> 00:21:39.500
teach at the Berklee College.

00:21:39.500 --> 00:21:41.680
A lot of times with
my piano students,

00:21:41.680 --> 00:21:43.110
when we work on
improvisation, I'm

00:21:43.110 --> 00:21:44.870
telling them you have
to record yourself.

00:21:44.870 --> 00:21:48.320
You have to turn on your
phone or whatever you've got,

00:21:48.320 --> 00:21:52.380
something just really easy
that you carry around with you.

00:21:52.380 --> 00:21:54.730
You record your improvisation,
record your group

00:21:54.730 --> 00:21:56.200
improvisations.

00:21:56.200 --> 00:21:58.750
And then listen back and
go, Yeah this is great.

00:21:58.750 --> 00:22:00.200
I didn't like this so much.

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:02.530
You know because that's
the way you learn.

00:22:02.530 --> 00:22:04.984
That's a great learning tool,
and I think sometimes it's

00:22:04.984 --> 00:22:07.400
one of those obvious things
that people don't think to do.

00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:10.280
When, like I said,
from my perspective,

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:13.160
it's a really great
way to develop

00:22:13.160 --> 00:22:14.420
a sense of what you're doing.

00:22:17.250 --> 00:22:22.530
So I'd like to
play one more tune.

00:22:22.530 --> 00:22:28.740
And then we'll maybe open it
up a little bit for you guys.

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:37.163
I'm wondering if we should do
something like the big violins,

00:22:37.163 --> 00:22:39.200
maybe?

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:40.750
FRIESEN: Like the
blues in E minor?

00:22:40.750 --> 00:22:43.470
RAY: Yeah.

00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:46.040
Do you want to?

00:22:46.040 --> 00:22:47.410
FRIESEN: Yeah.

00:22:47.410 --> 00:22:50.046
Have you guys worked on blues?

00:22:50.046 --> 00:22:51.760
Yeah, I'm sure you have.

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:54.360
Well again, for me as a
classically trained player,

00:22:54.360 --> 00:22:59.090
the blues were and are
really, really challenging.

00:22:59.090 --> 00:23:00.886
I mean just keeping
the form together,

00:23:00.886 --> 00:23:02.760
I really had to have
the paper in front of me

00:23:02.760 --> 00:23:05.290
for a long, long time just
to keep the twelve bar

00:23:05.290 --> 00:23:07.310
thing together.

00:23:07.310 --> 00:23:11.680
So but eventually it
became internalized.

00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:18.090
And here is a blues
that I came up with.

00:23:18.090 --> 00:23:23.374
I remember watching the shock
and awe invasion of Baghdad.

00:23:23.374 --> 00:23:25.290
I was just sitting in
front of this big screen

00:23:25.290 --> 00:23:27.331
TV with my cello, and what
I found myself playing

00:23:27.331 --> 00:23:33.020
was this one, Ray.

00:23:33.020 --> 00:23:35.515
[PLAYING MUSIC]

00:27:36.232 --> 00:27:38.712
[APPLAUSE]

00:27:44.080 --> 00:27:44.580
RAY: Cool.

00:27:44.580 --> 00:27:50.790
So, I have so much playing
that with you, Eugene.

00:27:50.790 --> 00:27:51.950
That's a gas.

00:27:51.950 --> 00:27:57.250
So obviously blues form, right?

00:27:57.250 --> 00:28:00.620
Were you're able to
keep track of it?

00:28:00.620 --> 00:28:02.020
Mostly you could, right?

00:28:02.020 --> 00:28:08.890
I mean that's one of things,
like I said before, as a jazz

00:28:08.890 --> 00:28:12.190
group we're unusual because
there's no bass and no drums.

00:28:12.190 --> 00:28:14.270
But of course, when
again this is something

00:28:14.270 --> 00:28:15.950
I preach to some
of my own students.

00:28:15.950 --> 00:28:19.270
It's like we're kind of
always the bass player.

00:28:19.270 --> 00:28:20.370
We're always the drummer.

00:28:20.370 --> 00:28:22.750
Even if you're playing a flute,
you're still the drummer,

00:28:22.750 --> 00:28:23.410
right?

00:28:23.410 --> 00:28:26.670
And I think that's one
of the things-- this

00:28:26.670 --> 00:28:30.990
is one of the kinds of
playing that we do as a trio

00:28:30.990 --> 00:28:35.330
where we actually
use those skills.

00:28:35.330 --> 00:28:38.800
We use those like, OK, let's--
we have this internal thing

00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:41.280
going on, this internal
metronome going on.

00:28:41.280 --> 00:28:43.200
We don't need the ride
cymbal necessarily

00:28:43.200 --> 00:28:45.320
because we're
keeping it together.

00:28:45.320 --> 00:28:48.780
And then of course we
because we like to have fun

00:28:48.780 --> 00:28:51.220
will throw caution
to the wind and do

00:28:51.220 --> 00:28:52.490
some crazy stuff for a while.

00:28:52.490 --> 00:28:54.850
But still in the back
of our mind, of course,

00:28:54.850 --> 00:28:56.600
we're listening, too.

00:28:56.600 --> 00:28:59.080
We're keeping
track of that time.

00:29:01.620 --> 00:29:02.790
Any questions about that?

00:29:02.790 --> 00:29:04.705
Comments?

00:29:04.705 --> 00:29:05.330
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:29:05.330 --> 00:29:10.070
I guess, I was wondering just
how-- [INAUDIBLE] on the piano,

00:29:10.070 --> 00:29:12.580
you were like playing really
quick fast notes like that

00:29:12.580 --> 00:29:15.355
[INAUDIBLE] the
cello, you ended,

00:29:15.355 --> 00:29:16.730
you know every
time you did this,

00:29:16.730 --> 00:29:18.240
you both ended at the same time.

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:20.450
And is it just that
you've played together

00:29:20.450 --> 00:29:21.700
long enough that you sort of--

00:29:21.700 --> 00:29:24.030
FRIESEN: Actually I
think that the moments

00:29:24.030 --> 00:29:26.280
you may be referring to are
the things about the blues

00:29:26.280 --> 00:29:30.330
form, where we would come
to the end of a phrase.

00:29:30.330 --> 00:29:35.390
And as Tim was hinting at,
or articulating before,

00:29:35.390 --> 00:29:38.940
when you feel like something
needs to change-- you know some

00:29:38.940 --> 00:29:41.000
of those double bars in
the music, in this case

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:43.870
the end of the 12 bar form,
where we are crescendo-ing,

00:29:43.870 --> 00:29:47.060
crescendo-ing getting crazier
and crazier and crazier.

00:29:47.060 --> 00:29:49.820
It just feels like, Oh wouldn't
that be a nice dramatic moment

00:29:49.820 --> 00:29:52.400
to just jump off the
cliff back into the head

00:29:52.400 --> 00:29:55.836
into that real,
real simple thing.

00:29:55.836 --> 00:29:58.899
AUDIENCE: I think two of the
times it happened at the end

00:29:58.899 --> 00:30:00.857
of the 12 bars, I think
one was just at the end

00:30:00.857 --> 00:30:02.269
of a [INAUDIBLE]--

00:30:02.269 --> 00:30:03.810
FRIESEN: And that's
just lucking out.

00:30:07.090 --> 00:30:08.840
And I think that's
probably what keeps

00:30:08.840 --> 00:30:11.050
all of us doing this is
just that lucking out

00:30:11.050 --> 00:30:13.940
part of the thing, just
not really knowing what's

00:30:13.940 --> 00:30:15.200
going to happen.

00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:17.400
And you know, none of
us wants to rehearse

00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:21.660
so much that you can
depend on those things.

00:30:21.660 --> 00:30:23.490
I love the very
expression, there's

00:30:23.490 --> 00:30:27.255
no substitute for a genuine
lack of preparation.

00:30:27.255 --> 00:30:29.880
Have you ever heard
that one before?

00:30:29.880 --> 00:30:31.940
Because sometimes
when you're really

00:30:31.940 --> 00:30:34.530
on the front of
your chair, you know

00:30:34.530 --> 00:30:39.400
you're really listening
in a way that is enhanced.

00:30:39.400 --> 00:30:43.180
And I think that is the
thing that keeps us musicians

00:30:43.180 --> 00:30:48.120
doing this is that incredibly
intense process of listening

00:30:48.120 --> 00:30:53.000
and presence, which by the way
is transmitted to the audience.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:55.160
And we get a lot of
energy from the audience.

00:30:55.160 --> 00:30:57.570
You probably know this
already, the value

00:30:57.570 --> 00:31:02.630
of doing this in front of people
is enhanced exponentially.

00:31:02.630 --> 00:31:06.570
And the quality of being in the
audience when you're witnessing

00:31:06.570 --> 00:31:09.080
something that is
happening in real time

00:31:09.080 --> 00:31:10.910
is something tangible.

00:31:10.910 --> 00:31:14.140
Not only that, but as scientific
research has pointed out,

00:31:14.140 --> 00:31:17.180
our brain research,
listeners will

00:31:17.180 --> 00:31:19.920
have a similar kind
of experience brain

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:22.710
experience as the performers.

00:31:22.710 --> 00:31:25.590
So we really get
this vicarious kind

00:31:25.590 --> 00:31:27.480
of thrill, this
kind of vicarious

00:31:27.480 --> 00:31:30.740
high just from being in
the presence of something

00:31:30.740 --> 00:31:32.870
incredible that's going on.

00:31:32.870 --> 00:31:36.640
Which is why I'm quite sure
that live performance will never

00:31:36.640 --> 00:31:37.140
die.

00:31:37.140 --> 00:31:40.900
You know, once we get over this
infatuation with the screens,

00:31:40.900 --> 00:31:44.530
I think people will
be back at concerts

00:31:44.530 --> 00:31:45.730
and live events like that.

00:31:45.730 --> 00:31:48.040
And certainly the thing that
keeps us musicians at it

00:31:48.040 --> 00:31:52.230
because there again the
enhanced listening that we

00:31:52.230 --> 00:31:55.320
can do in rehearsal is very
different than it feels

00:31:55.320 --> 00:31:57.000
like from playing for you guys.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.980
You know there's an
extra level of attention

00:31:59.980 --> 00:32:02.340
that comes to it that is--

00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:05.320
And sometimes it's just a tiny
little switch in your brain

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:07.570
that makes all the
difference in the world.

00:32:07.570 --> 00:32:08.530
It's so amazing.

00:32:08.530 --> 00:32:11.190
You probably know this from
the musical work you've done

00:32:11.190 --> 00:32:12.520
or the writing you've done.

00:32:12.520 --> 00:32:15.340
Sometimes you'll sit
down and you'll just,

00:32:15.340 --> 00:32:19.090
your body will just type
something really cool.

00:32:19.090 --> 00:32:23.200
And you didn't even mean to do
it, it just kind of happened.

00:32:23.200 --> 00:32:26.194
You can't force
that kind of thing.

00:32:26.194 --> 00:32:26.860
RAY: Absolutely.

00:32:26.860 --> 00:32:30.500
FRIESEN: Well, where should
we go from here, Tim?

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:35.740
RAY: So I wanted to
do this actually.

00:32:35.740 --> 00:32:38.650
I wanted to hand out--
because I know some of you

00:32:38.650 --> 00:32:41.120
have to leave early.

00:32:41.120 --> 00:32:44.930
So my thinking for this
course-- you know, it is school.

00:32:44.930 --> 00:32:47.670
You do have to
have an assignment.

00:32:47.670 --> 00:32:51.620
So I'm going to hand
out a tune, and I

00:32:51.620 --> 00:32:53.290
want to get back
to the improvising

00:32:53.290 --> 00:32:55.260
in a diatonic setting
that Eugene and I were

00:32:55.260 --> 00:32:55.970
doing earlier.

00:32:55.970 --> 00:32:57.345
And that's what
I want to do kind

00:32:57.345 --> 00:33:00.810
of with some of the
rest of this class.

00:33:00.810 --> 00:33:03.900
But for the
assignment, I actually

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:05.460
want you guys to
work on something

00:33:05.460 --> 00:33:08.430
similar to what we
were just doing.

00:33:08.430 --> 00:33:10.930
We have a song, I'll
pass it out now.

00:33:10.930 --> 00:33:15.530
We have a song in our trio
repertoire called "Cargasian."

00:33:15.530 --> 00:33:17.320
This is it.

00:33:17.320 --> 00:33:18.070
FRIESEN: Oh, cool.

