00:34:08.679 --> 00:34:13.260
RAY: So there's a melody
line, which you can see.

00:34:13.260 --> 00:34:15.850
And this is also a
12 bar blues form.

00:34:15.850 --> 00:34:20.300
So there's like a number one,
number two, number three.

00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:22.340
These are the
different sections.

00:34:22.340 --> 00:34:24.780
Number three you don't
have to worry about.

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:27.219
The chord changes so much,
those are mostly just

00:34:27.219 --> 00:34:29.469
for my benefit as a pianist.

00:34:29.469 --> 00:34:31.500
When we play the melody,
we all play in unison.

00:34:31.500 --> 00:34:33.870
In other words, like
I said, no chords.

00:34:33.870 --> 00:34:35.909
It's all just playing
this melody in unison.

00:34:35.909 --> 00:34:38.600
So of course, the first
part of your assignment

00:34:38.600 --> 00:34:40.790
is to be able to play
the melody in time.

00:34:40.790 --> 00:34:44.070
It's similar tempo
to what we just did.

00:34:44.070 --> 00:34:47.159
[HUMMING]

00:34:47.159 --> 00:34:51.614
Nice little medium
swing kind of groove.

00:34:51.614 --> 00:34:52.530
You have to watch out.

00:34:52.530 --> 00:34:54.363
At the end there's some
three four measures.

00:34:54.363 --> 00:34:58.700
You do have to play the
three four measures.

00:34:58.700 --> 00:35:02.170
And then you see at the end on
the bottom of the page, solo

00:35:02.170 --> 00:35:03.520
over G minor blues.

00:35:03.520 --> 00:35:06.840
Now I know you guys have done
some work with the blues.

00:35:06.840 --> 00:35:10.120
These are very basic-- this
is sort of a basic Minor blues

00:35:10.120 --> 00:35:14.020
form, 12 bars.

00:35:14.020 --> 00:35:16.670
And basically, what I
would like for you to do

00:35:16.670 --> 00:35:21.660
is to take some of the
motives from the melody.

00:35:21.660 --> 00:35:24.650
And maybe Eugene
and I will play it

00:35:24.650 --> 00:35:27.290
once real quickly just
so you can hear it.

00:35:27.290 --> 00:35:29.200
Take some of the motives
from this melody.

00:35:29.200 --> 00:35:30.850
There's a few key things.

00:35:30.850 --> 00:35:33.350
I'm sure once you hear them,
you'll be able to identify them

00:35:33.350 --> 00:35:36.560
or you can circle
them or whatever.

00:35:36.560 --> 00:35:38.400
Work with some of these motives.

00:35:38.400 --> 00:35:42.910
Come up with some blues
improvisational ideas.

00:35:42.910 --> 00:35:46.320
And then what I'd like to
do when Greg and I come back

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:48.710
on Monday is we'll
do essentially

00:35:48.710 --> 00:35:50.010
what Eugene and I were doing.

00:35:50.010 --> 00:35:53.590
I'll have you team up
in maybe twos or threes

00:35:53.590 --> 00:35:56.390
and do some improvisation
over the blues.

00:35:56.390 --> 00:36:04.130
And again a good way to
practice that is sit down

00:36:04.130 --> 00:36:05.390
with a metronome, right?

00:36:05.390 --> 00:36:07.890
I mean obviously, sitting down
with your friends is a better

00:36:07.890 --> 00:36:11.390
way to practice, but sitting
down with a metronome,

00:36:11.390 --> 00:36:15.620
having the metronome go, just
practicing improvisation.

00:36:15.620 --> 00:36:19.830
Like I say, we'll play
through some of these figures

00:36:19.830 --> 00:36:23.740
and have you kind of
identify some of those

00:36:23.740 --> 00:36:27.050
and maybe try to work those into
some of your improvisations.

00:36:27.050 --> 00:36:28.550
Can we play this
real quick, Eugene?

00:36:28.550 --> 00:36:30.030
FRIESEN: Let's find out.

00:36:30.030 --> 00:36:31.956
RAY: I guess we'll find out.

00:36:31.956 --> 00:36:33.080
FRIESEN: It's been a while.

00:36:33.080 --> 00:36:37.690
RAY: So like I said, we
always play this just

00:36:37.690 --> 00:36:42.270
in unison, the melody.

00:36:42.270 --> 00:36:45.020
On the way out, you'll hear
tonight at the concert,

00:36:45.020 --> 00:36:47.380
we try to do a sort of a
cannon with the melody.

00:36:47.380 --> 00:36:48.751
But we won't try the cannon now.

00:36:48.751 --> 00:36:50.250
FRIESEN: So for now
we're just going

00:36:50.250 --> 00:36:51.915
to read through three sections?

00:36:51.915 --> 00:36:53.706
RAY: We're just going
to read through them.

00:36:53.706 --> 00:36:55.710
FRIESEN: Just to
give the sound of it.

00:36:55.710 --> 00:36:57.310
RAY: A one, two three.

00:36:57.310 --> 00:36:58.340
[PLAYING MUSIC]

00:37:59.905 --> 00:38:03.390
RAY: Right, we're ending, yeah.

00:38:03.390 --> 00:38:05.605
And then the nice
diminished chord.

00:38:05.605 --> 00:38:07.230
That's what we always
teach you, right?

00:38:07.230 --> 00:38:09.700
End on a diminished chord?

00:38:09.700 --> 00:38:10.842
Good compositional.

00:38:10.842 --> 00:38:12.900
FRIESEN: Isn't that
a great melody?

00:38:12.900 --> 00:38:17.482
I mean, that's like just the
coolest, Buddhist design never.

00:38:17.482 --> 00:38:18.440
RAY: It's like a haiku.

00:38:18.440 --> 00:38:21.188
FRIESEN: All that
space around you.

00:38:21.188 --> 00:38:22.940
AUDIENCE: Why do you
put in bar lines?

00:38:22.940 --> 00:38:24.560
What's the point?

00:38:24.560 --> 00:38:26.850
FRIESEN: I think the
point is that we always

00:38:26.850 --> 00:38:28.890
are really aligned.

00:38:28.890 --> 00:38:31.112
We feel the beat together.

00:38:31.112 --> 00:38:32.070
And you have to, right?

00:38:32.070 --> 00:38:32.670
To play that.

00:38:32.670 --> 00:38:34.527
AUDIENCE: You have
to, but I don't

00:38:34.527 --> 00:38:35.809
feel the bar lines at all.

00:38:35.809 --> 00:38:36.600
FRIESEN: Don't you?

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:38.322
Well, great.

00:38:38.322 --> 00:38:39.030
RAY: That's good.

00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:39.960
We like that.

00:38:39.960 --> 00:38:41.376
FRIESEN: As Tim
mentioned, we know

00:38:41.376 --> 00:38:44.310
we often do this in
unison then we'll play it

00:38:44.310 --> 00:38:48.770
as a round at a bar and two
beats, is that how we do it?

00:38:48.770 --> 00:38:49.520
Or one beat?

00:38:49.520 --> 00:38:52.533
RAY: We start off the
three of us on the way out.

00:38:52.533 --> 00:38:54.720
We play it unison together.

00:38:54.720 --> 00:38:56.950
Like I said, coming
tonight, you'll hear it.

00:38:56.950 --> 00:39:01.003
Then we do the improvisation,
which is like-- Whoops,

00:39:01.003 --> 00:39:02.448
I lost my microphone.

00:39:05.790 --> 00:39:08.430
The improvisation,
which is all three

00:39:08.430 --> 00:39:10.120
of us improvising
at the same time.

00:39:10.120 --> 00:39:13.080
It's not really like a
typical, one person's

00:39:13.080 --> 00:39:15.380
a soloist and another
person's an accompanist.

00:39:15.380 --> 00:39:17.850
FRIESEN: It's really
efficient time wise.

00:39:17.850 --> 00:39:19.360
RAY: It's true.

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:22.406
Makes for a nice
short presentation.

00:39:22.406 --> 00:39:24.530
And then on the way out,
yeah as Eugene was saying,

00:39:24.530 --> 00:39:26.810
we do a round.

00:39:26.810 --> 00:39:32.300
We start off trumpet and then
one measure later is you.

00:39:32.300 --> 00:39:33.800
FRIESEN: At the bar, right.

00:39:33.800 --> 00:39:35.200
RAY: One bar.

00:39:35.200 --> 00:39:37.219
And then that piano
comes in one bar later.

00:39:37.219 --> 00:39:38.760
So you get sort of
this round effect.

00:39:38.760 --> 00:39:40.860
And then when we
get to section two,

00:39:40.860 --> 00:39:44.197
we condense it to two beats.

00:39:44.197 --> 00:39:45.780
And then when we get
to section three,

00:39:45.780 --> 00:39:47.190
we condense it to one beat.

00:39:47.190 --> 00:39:49.980
So we're only separated
by one beat apiece.

00:39:49.980 --> 00:39:51.920
It's kind of fun.

00:39:51.920 --> 00:39:54.642
It's sort of a fun game.

00:39:54.642 --> 00:39:59.120
AUDIENCE: Why did you decide to,
for example in measure seven,

00:39:59.120 --> 00:40:03.690
write a C flat instead
of the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:05.700
RAY: That's a very
good question.

00:40:05.700 --> 00:40:10.180
I mean you might have to ask the
composer, Greg, who's not here.

00:40:10.180 --> 00:40:17.880
But my guess would be, although
there's no key signature.

00:40:17.880 --> 00:40:21.180
I mean I think of this
as in the key of G minor,

00:40:21.180 --> 00:40:22.270
which has got flats.

00:40:22.270 --> 00:40:25.240
So I think that's probably
what he would say.

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:28.280
Although again, not having a
key signature that probably

00:40:28.280 --> 00:40:29.519
doesn't make a lot of sense.

00:40:29.519 --> 00:40:30.060
I don't know.

00:40:30.060 --> 00:40:31.520
What do you think?

00:40:31.520 --> 00:40:33.140
FRIESEN: I think
you're right now.

00:40:33.140 --> 00:40:35.440
RAY: But I think the idea
is that it's in a flat key,

00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:40.812
and so C flat would be a little
bit more conventional, for lack

00:40:40.812 --> 00:40:41.520
of a better word.

00:40:41.520 --> 00:40:43.880
I'm sort of one of those
guys where I actually

00:40:43.880 --> 00:40:47.037
prefer to see B natural if
I'm sight reading something.

00:40:47.037 --> 00:40:48.620
AUDIENCE: There is
a B natural, right?

00:40:48.620 --> 00:40:51.180
RAY: That's true that's true.

00:40:51.180 --> 00:40:51.680
OK.

00:40:51.680 --> 00:40:55.095
Well, now you've
completely stumped me.

00:40:55.095 --> 00:40:57.250
FRIESEN: It could be
the software, too.

00:40:57.250 --> 00:41:01.530
RAY: It could be the notation
software, which is oftentimes

00:41:01.530 --> 00:41:06.100
when musicians make unusual
choices, it's not actually

00:41:06.100 --> 00:41:08.732
a choice, if you
know what I mean.

00:41:08.732 --> 00:41:10.315
HARVEY: Can I just
make another point.

00:41:10.315 --> 00:41:13.151
I think it would be
interesting to ask

00:41:13.151 --> 00:41:14.734
Greg about when he
comes by on Monday.

00:41:14.734 --> 00:41:18.860
Because actually a lot of these
phrases in number one and two

00:41:18.860 --> 00:41:23.197
seem to be almost three beat
phrases if you look at it.

00:41:23.197 --> 00:41:23.905
RAY: That's true.

00:41:23.905 --> 00:41:26.112
HARVEY: --it really
anticipates and it then it

00:41:26.112 --> 00:41:28.024
goes into three, per se.

00:41:28.024 --> 00:41:30.414
So it's an interesting
[INAUDIBLE]

00:41:30.414 --> 00:41:33.210
with the kind of five
integral beats or whatever.

00:41:36.089 --> 00:41:36.880
RAY: I would agree.

00:41:36.880 --> 00:41:37.671
Yeah, you're right.

00:41:37.671 --> 00:41:40.739
They're not typical
phrase lengths.

00:41:40.739 --> 00:41:41.530
Yeah, you're right.

00:41:41.530 --> 00:41:44.620
There's a lot of threes,
three beat phrases.

00:41:47.650 --> 00:41:50.610
Anyway, the other thing I just
wanted to point out quickly

00:41:50.610 --> 00:41:55.330
was just, like I said,
you see obviously,

00:41:55.330 --> 00:41:59.940
if you're looking for
motives to grab onto.

00:41:59.940 --> 00:42:01.657
Well, maybe you
can tell me what's

00:42:01.657 --> 00:42:03.490
one thing you might
circle if you were going

00:42:03.490 --> 00:42:05.910
to try to pick out things
that make this melody

00:42:05.910 --> 00:42:07.880
unique or different
or interesting?

00:42:15.530 --> 00:42:16.920
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:16.920 --> 00:42:18.520
RAY: Right.

00:42:18.520 --> 00:42:23.310
The little ascending thing
at the beginning, right?

00:42:23.310 --> 00:42:26.630
You see that towards the end.

00:42:31.820 --> 00:42:34.190
You see it actually
all over the place.

00:42:34.190 --> 00:42:36.434
The second line.

00:42:36.434 --> 00:42:37.225
And the third line.

00:42:40.630 --> 00:42:43.230
Little ascending intervals.

00:42:43.230 --> 00:42:46.890
That's a nice one.

00:42:46.890 --> 00:42:49.276
How about the thing in section
two, the repeated note?

00:42:53.570 --> 00:42:56.340
That comes back again and
again in section two, right?

00:42:59.741 --> 00:43:01.490
And then the other
thing I would point out

00:43:01.490 --> 00:43:04.650
would be maybe this sort
of quarter note triplet

00:43:04.650 --> 00:43:07.630
thing, which comes in
once in the first section

00:43:07.630 --> 00:43:11.750
and then comes in again
in the second section.

00:43:11.750 --> 00:43:15.450
Again these are
all things you can

00:43:15.450 --> 00:43:19.150
try to incorporate
into an improvisation.

00:43:19.150 --> 00:43:20.530
So like I said,
this would be-- I

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:23.970
think will be an interesting
thing to work on.

00:43:23.970 --> 00:43:30.310
And we'll get you guys playing
on this tune on Monday.

00:43:30.310 --> 00:43:31.130
Cool.

00:43:31.130 --> 00:43:34.520
So let's see.

00:43:37.380 --> 00:43:39.450
Getting back in kind
of the diatonic thing.

00:43:39.450 --> 00:43:42.130
I wanted to do that.

00:43:42.130 --> 00:43:44.000
Get you guys playing
a little bit.

00:43:49.986 --> 00:43:51.360
I guess I'll hand
out this thing.

00:43:55.400 --> 00:44:00.040
So basically, I mean this
is something you probably

00:44:00.040 --> 00:44:03.710
don't even need to look at, but
what we're going to try now,

00:44:03.710 --> 00:44:05.890
get into a little
bit, is just G major.

00:44:05.890 --> 00:44:08.970
And we're going to spend
some time in G major.

00:44:08.970 --> 00:44:11.240
So I hope you like G major.

00:44:11.240 --> 00:44:15.330
Conveniently a transposed
to A major for those of you

00:44:15.330 --> 00:44:16.442
who don't read.

00:44:16.442 --> 00:44:18.400
FRIESEN: Did you do the
transposition yourself?

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:19.930
RAY: I did the
transposition myself.

00:44:19.930 --> 00:44:21.650
This was not done on a computer.

00:44:21.650 --> 00:44:24.420
This was done by hand,
the old fashioned way,

00:44:24.420 --> 00:44:25.740
with a needle and thread.

00:44:28.580 --> 00:44:31.501
Anyway, like I said, I
don't even necessarily

00:44:31.501 --> 00:44:33.000
why I'm handing
this out because I'm

00:44:33.000 --> 00:44:37.040
sure you guys all know
what a G major scale is.

00:44:37.040 --> 00:44:37.950
Well, Mark doesn't.

00:44:37.950 --> 00:44:40.190
We'll get Mark clued in.

00:44:46.530 --> 00:44:48.910
But I thought this might
be an interesting thing

00:44:48.910 --> 00:44:51.417
to spend some time with.

00:44:51.417 --> 00:44:53.500
And if we have time at the
end, maybe Eugene and I

00:44:53.500 --> 00:44:57.610
will play another piece from our
repertoire, our vast repertoire

00:44:57.610 --> 00:45:01.150
of duo songs.

00:45:01.150 --> 00:45:08.960
But basically, like I
said, the whole idea

00:45:08.960 --> 00:45:13.650
of doing improvisation in
a diatonic setting-- which

00:45:13.650 --> 00:45:16.070
as you heard from the
first piece we played,

00:45:16.070 --> 00:45:21.440
can really go as far
as you want it to go,

00:45:21.440 --> 00:45:26.417
or it can stay kind of
small, is a really, I

00:45:26.417 --> 00:45:28.000
think, an interesting
way to practice.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:29.708
And I think it's a
really interesting way

00:45:29.708 --> 00:45:32.550
to kind of develop a lot
of the improvisation skills

00:45:32.550 --> 00:45:35.910
that you use in other kinds of
improvisation, including atonal

00:45:35.910 --> 00:45:37.680
and jazz.

00:45:37.680 --> 00:45:40.440
Like I said, any
kind of improvisation

00:45:40.440 --> 00:45:44.380
you do, I think the
diatonic version of improv

00:45:44.380 --> 00:45:48.090
is I think a good way to--
it's a good, as Eugene said,

00:45:48.090 --> 00:45:51.190
limitation, a good way to
restrict the amount of things

00:45:51.190 --> 00:45:53.750
you have to think about.

00:45:53.750 --> 00:45:57.410
So it sounds like someone
is knocking on the door.

00:46:00.230 --> 00:46:01.240
Let's do this.

00:46:04.231 --> 00:46:05.980
I haven't really
necessarily planned this.

00:46:05.980 --> 00:46:07.610
But I'm going to do this.

00:46:07.610 --> 00:46:11.260
Eugene and I will do a little
bit of a G major improvisation.

00:46:11.260 --> 00:46:14.570
The other thing I'll point out
on the bottom of this page,

00:46:14.570 --> 00:46:16.785
again these are all
diatonic chords.

00:46:19.520 --> 00:46:21.080
Chris, you're a
piano player, right?

00:46:21.080 --> 00:46:25.106
Are there any other
piano players here today?

00:46:25.106 --> 00:46:25.606
Cool.

00:46:32.850 --> 00:46:35.990
So but for anybody who's
doing chordal instruments-- I

00:46:35.990 --> 00:46:41.150
see the banjo and the guitar--
obviously, one of the things,

00:46:41.150 --> 00:46:45.270
and of course Eugene
is as well versed

00:46:45.270 --> 00:46:47.160
in playing chordal
accompaniments,

00:46:47.160 --> 00:46:50.330
probably more so than
pretty much any other cello

00:46:50.330 --> 00:46:52.770
player I've ever met.

00:46:52.770 --> 00:46:54.017
It's one of his strengths.

00:46:54.017 --> 00:46:56.350
Again it's something you'll
see more evidence of tonight

00:46:56.350 --> 00:46:56.975
in the concert.

00:47:00.320 --> 00:47:03.900
But you see I've just drawn
out some basic diatonic chords.

00:47:03.900 --> 00:47:05.950
If we're in the key
of G major, these

00:47:05.950 --> 00:47:07.190
are all just seventh chords.

00:47:07.190 --> 00:47:07.680
And it's not necessary.

00:47:07.680 --> 00:47:09.680
It doesn't mean you have
to play seventh chords.

00:47:09.680 --> 00:47:13.060
But these are examples.

00:47:13.060 --> 00:47:20.380
G major, A minor, B minor,
C major, D seven, E minor,

00:47:20.380 --> 00:47:22.880
and then the minor
seven with a flat five

00:47:22.880 --> 00:47:25.420
if you go to the seventh
degree, F sharp, right.

00:47:25.420 --> 00:47:31.300
So these are all, in terms of
harmony, good source material.

00:47:31.300 --> 00:47:32.800
It doesn't necessarily
mean that you

00:47:32.800 --> 00:47:36.690
have to move them around a
lot or move around at all.

00:47:36.690 --> 00:47:39.790
Of course, but it's
again, thinking back

00:47:39.790 --> 00:47:42.170
to that first tune
we played, just

00:47:42.170 --> 00:47:46.410
using a major scale
as a source material,

00:47:46.410 --> 00:47:49.010
there are just so many
options in terms of harmony.

00:47:49.010 --> 00:47:53.060
Sometimes like I said, those of
us who come from a jazz world,

00:47:53.060 --> 00:47:57.260
we're used to things
moving more, moving quickly

00:47:57.260 --> 00:48:00.670
and in a less diatonic fashion.

00:48:00.670 --> 00:48:04.550
But again, like I said, just in
the diatonic areas, you know,

00:48:04.550 --> 00:48:06.530
you've got 7 chords right here.

00:48:06.530 --> 00:48:08.030
And then you've got
all these chords

00:48:08.030 --> 00:48:09.410
with different kinds of roots.

00:48:09.410 --> 00:48:14.570
You know you've got G major
with a third in the bottom.

00:48:14.570 --> 00:48:19.900
You can do a C major with
the fifth on the bottom.

00:48:19.900 --> 00:48:22.540
You can do again, like I
said, all of these things.

00:48:34.600 --> 00:48:35.930
You've got a lot.

00:48:35.930 --> 00:48:39.280
